title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Leicester Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Leicester Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

title: Motor Vehicle Accident Report 23-067187 on 7/29/2023

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Motor Vehicle Accident Report 23-067187 on 7/29/2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Body camera footage of Georgia DeKalb County Police Officer Shatasha Anderson # 3591 on 7/29/2023 around 15:30.  Officer Anderson took statements from two individuals at a motor vehicle accident at Candler Road near Ember Drive, case # 23-067187.  Officer Anderson stated in the incident report that her body-worm camera was activated.  We request the video of the entire event please.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Chavez

After reviewing your request, it has been determined that the requested documents if they exist are subject to release under the Open Records Act, except those records that are part of an open investigation pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 50-18-72(a)(4). It will take approximatelyfive (10) days to search, retrieve, copy and/or provide the records and invoice. A cost estimate will be emailed to you soon; you will then let us know if you are willing to pay for the video or not.


Thank You,
David Rodriguez, Paralegal
DeKalb County Police Department
Open Records Unit

title: Child care provider data 2019-present (Connecticut Office Of Early Childhood)

communications.subject: Connecticut Freedom of Information Act Request: Child care provider data 2019-present (Connecticut Office Of Early Childhood)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Historical licensing data for all licensed child care providers (active and closed) that were open anytime from 1/1/19-present:
1) Provider name or ID
2) Provider address
3) Latest license issue date and expiration date 
4) First license issue date
5) Enrollment, including dates on which enrollment was recorded (by child age groups if available)
6) Capacity, including dates on which capacity was recorded (by child age groups if available)
7) Prices, including dates on which prices were recorded (by child age groups if available)
8) Quality Rating and Improvement System (QRIS) scores, including dates on which scores were recorded
9) Any additional provider data that your agency collects

If electronic records from before 1/1/19 are available, I’d be happy to collect them as well.

I also request that, if possible and pursuant to Conn. Gen. Stat. § 1-212(d), fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest and not made for commercial gain. The requested documents will be made available to the public at MuckRock.com.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 4 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Gabrielle Pepin

communications.subject: FOI Records Request :: R000030-120323
communications.communication:
Dear Gabrielle Pepin: 
 
 
This message is an acknowledgement that the Connecticut Office of Early Childhood received your Freedom of Information Act request on 12/3/2023. It was given the reference number R000030-120323 for tracking purposes. 
 
 
This letter does not constitute a denial of your request. Rather, in accordance with the Freedom of Information Act, we are in the process of researching and gathering documentation which may be responsive to it. Once the documents are gathered, we will then conduct a review to determine if statutory exemptions to disclosure may apply to some or all of the documents. Upon completion of that review, we will be able to provide you with any responsive, non-exempt documents. 
 
Please note the department reserves the right to charge any such other fees as may be appropriate pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act. 
You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you'll receive an email when your request has been completed. Again, thank you for using the OEC FOI Records Center. 
Connecticut Office of Early Childhood

communications.subject: [Records Center] FOI Records Request :: R000030-120323
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
RE: FOI Records Request of December 03, 2023, Reference # R000030-120323. Dear Gabrielle Pepin, We are writing in response to Freedom of Information Act Request # R000030-120323.  We have reviewed our files and determined that our agency has responsive records.  Those records have been uploaded to the GovQA portal and can be accessed here: FOI Records Request - R000030-120323  You can generate a roster of licensed or license-exempt programs by using the eLicense website. There you would select Child Care Licensing Program or Youth Camp Licensing Program, choose the type of facility such as family child care home, child care center/group child care home or license-exempt. You can also select the type of information you are looking for- recently open or closed, or get a list of all active programs. These rosters will have information such as name, license number, address, phone number, email address and more. https://www.ctoec.org/licensing/look-up-providers-and-programs/  additional program information can be found at https://www.211childcare.org/ 
Sincerely, 
Legal

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Milford Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

title: Data Breach Union County FL

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, we hereby request the following information:

Your agency name
Your agency state
Your agency type   Business, Education K12, Education Higher
Your agency CEO

Breach is defined for this request as
A: An external actor that forcibly entered the system and accessed information
B: An internal actor that released or shared information that was not appropriate to share or shared intentionally without regard for entity protocol.

Please list any breach that was reported using the following format for the time period July 1, 2021 until July 1, 2023. Label each breach logically as Breach 1 or Breach 2, etc.*List each breach categorized as a document or an email as a separate breach.

For each breach provide the following information
1. Was this event for documents or email?
2. Date breach was reported
3. The position of the person reporting the breach
4. Highest position of  administration the breach was reported to for the agency
5. Was the process or procedure for evaluating and notifying those impacted followed? 
6. Were stakeholders with breached data notified?   If so, what timeline after the breach was reported (weeks, days, hours)  to the CEO listed above was the notification sent to those impacted?
7. What method(s) was used to notify stakeholders of the breach? Example, newspaper, social media, email, phone, mail, etc.
8. Was any protection such as credit monitoring or other protective opportunities provided to stakeholders affected?
9. Was the breached information considered protected under HIPAA or FERPA?
10. Count of records breached for category 1 above. (Emails and documents should NOT be included in the same count but reported as separate events even if the same date)
11. If the agency's process or procedure for evaluating and notification were not followed, what was the reasoning and by whom was the decision made to not follow the process or procedure?

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,
FOIA Disclosure Group

Good afternoon,

We are still researching this matter and will need more time to review the information to be able to provide an accurate response. Thank you for your patience.

To Whom It May Concern:
Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, we hereby request the following information:
Your agency name Union County School District
Your agency state Florida
Your agency type   Business, Education K12, Education Higher Education K-12
Your agency CEO Mike Ripplinger
Breach is defined for this request as
A: An external actor that forcibly entered the system and accessed information
B: An internal actor that released or shared information that was not appropriate to share or shared intentionally without regard for entity protocol.
Please list any breach that was reported using the following format for the time period July 1, 2021 until July 1, 2023. Label each breach logically as Breach 1 or Breach 2, etc.*List each breach categorized as a document or an email as a separate breach.
For each breach provide the following information

1. Was this event for documents or email? 
Breach 1 - Documents - Upon review of the documents reported to some members of the Critical Incident Response Team (CIRT) as a breach, the documents in question were not found to meet the District Incident Response Plan definition of a breach. 
Breach 2 - Emails - Upon review of the emails reported to some members of the Critical Incident Response Team (CIRT) as a breach, these emails in question were not found to meet the District Incident Response Plan definition of a breach.

2. Date breach was reported
Breach 1 - 5/19/2022
Breach 2 - 10/31/2022

3. The position of the person reporting the breach 
Breach 1 - MIS Director
Breach 2 - MIS Director

4. Highest position of administration the breach was reported to for the agency
Breach 1 - Superintendent
Breach 2 - Superintendent

5. Was the process or procedure for evaluating and notifying those impacted followed? 
Breach 1 - MIS Director notified two of the Critical Incident Response team members, however the complete team was not convened because the nature of the documents were not deemed a breach as defined by the District’s IRP.
Breach 2 - MIS Director notified two of the Critical Incident Response team members, however the complete team was not convened because the nature of the emails were not deemed a breach as defined by the District’s IRP.

6. Were stakeholders with breached data notified?   If so, what timeline after the breach was reported (weeks, days, hours)  to the CEO listed above was the notification sent to those impacted?
Breach 1 - No, upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 
Breach 2 - No, upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 

7. What method(s) was used to notify stakeholders of the breach? Example, newspaper, social media, email, phone, mail, etc.
Breach 1 - None, due to the understanding of the requirements listed in the Incident Response Plan
Breach 2 - None, due to the understanding of the requirements listed in the Incident Response Plan

8. Was any protection such as credit monitoring or other protective opportunities provided to stakeholders affected?
Breach 1 - The incident did not result in the release of personal information as defined in the District’s IRP 
Breach 2 - The incident did not result in the release of personal information as defined in the District’s IRP 

9. Was the breached information considered protected under HIPAA or FERPA?
Breach 1 - FERPA
Breach 2 - FERPA

10. Count of records breached for category 1 above. (Emails and documents should NOT be included in the same count but reported as separate events even if the same date)
Breach 1 - 1246
Breach 2 - 1067 - This total indicates the number of times the email in question had any type of activity, not necessarily resulting in any type of breach. 

11. If the agency's process or procedure for evaluating and notification were not followed, what was the reasoning and by whom was the decision made to not follow the process or procedure?
Breach 1 - Upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 
Breach 2 - Upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.
Sincerely,
FOIA Disclosure Group

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request #20230822
communications.communication:
After multiple reviews some information in your latest response created  confusion and further need for clarification.  The group wishes to make sure it understands the entity's working document regarding a data breach as it relates to the steps the entity took to resolve the issue.
Initially your response was the CEO unilaterally determined (outside the scope of the entity's process) the events were not critical and the sharing and viewing of protected information was not a breach (Hillsborough Schools just reported an event as a breach where only 250 records were improperly viewed, far less than your entity).

In a recent followup dated August 11, 2023, it was stated the MIS Director at the time, followed up with two members of the critical response team on each event.

1. Please give the name, title and email address of these members that were contacted from the team, the MIS Director's name and email address when the breach occurred , the date they were contacted by the MIS Director and the content of the meeting regarding EACH event. A statement will be requested from these individuals.

2. Please send the names and email addresses of those reported as creating the breach.

3. Also, this is by no means  saying the information is not correct but just wanted to confirm for the official record responded to on August 22, 2023.  As of the date of the second breach reporting, October 31, 2022, the official statement is no other emails or document sharing occurred between the individuals that created the breach after this reporting date.  This is not saying the information is not correct but it seems rare that the email and communications between the individuals involved in the breach ceased on the same day the breach was reported. Is that still the official statement?

As of the date of the second breach reporting, October 31, 2022, the official statement is no other emails or document sharing occurred between the individuals that created the breach after this reporting date. This is not saying the information is not correct but it seems rare that the email and communications between the individuals involved in the breach ceased on the same day the breach was reported. Is that still the official statement?

After IT further investigated, while the second breach was reported October 31, 2022, the last sharing or communication was August 30, 2022 prior to the second breach notification.

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request #Complete
communications.communication:
Thanks so much for your response.

Your  response dated August 11, 2023  and later mentions by name, MIS Coordinator (or Director in other responses from December 4, 2023 response) Lanier Clyatt as the one who met with two members of the team.

In the December 4  2023 response the names and positions of MIS Coordinator and Chris Mecusker, Director of Personnel, were the two that the MIS Coordinator contacted. That is really one member contacted for an opinion on the breach being valid to report to those affected or  are we misunderstanding your response correctly?

Also in the August 11, 2023 response it was stated the Superintendent determined the documents that were categorized as FERPA content was not critical and now the MIS Coordinator or Director that in this same response date was the one that reported it. This is confusing as the MIS Director would have reported it if it was not critical to begin with.

Please  send  this request  below to the members you mentioned.
MIS Coordinator - clyattl@union.k12.fl.us 
Director of Personnel - Mecuskerc@union.k12.fl.us

Request  starts on  next line

You are being included as part of a public records request. 
Your information was obtained from a request sent to your entity regarding a data breach.

Please verify that you as a committee member were contacted regarding these breaches.
If there were any documents, meeting notes or email  regarding this meeting or sharing information regarding these breaches please include them.
Please give the date of the meeting and the location. 

As it stands there were only the MIS Coordinator and Director of Personnel that made the decision that the breaches were not critical. Please state according to the records release how the decision was made and how your CIRT document supported this decision.

You may view the discussion of  the public records request here.
https://www.muckrock.com/foi/union-county-10464/untitled-149460/

Thanks in advance for your assistance.
Freedom of Information Act Disclosure Group

My apologies for the confusion,  former MIS Coordinator, Lanier Clyatt and Director of Personnel, Chris Mecusker, were the only members of the CIRT aware of this incident.

Please see the attachments which include the communications Mr. Mecusker provided regarding the incident. 

Mr. Clyatt is no longer employed with the District. 

The District will not be providing any information that does not already exist in a record as defined by Florida Statute 119.011. By answering questions or providing statements, we are creating a record that does not already exist.

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Easton Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Easton Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

communications.subject: RE: FOIA #GFO-2024-00640-F Acknowledgement
communications.communication:
Good morning Mr. Fritz,

I wanted to provide an update regarding your FOIA request.  During our search and review process, we learned that negotiations are still very much underway.  As such, the documents responsive to your request cannot be released at this time.  It is anticipated that the majority of award negotiations will be completed towards the end of January 2024.  That said, I would recommend waiting until February to ensure its wrapped up.

This in mind, I would like to give you the opportunity to withdraw your request with no further actions required at this time, and re-submit your request at a later date.  We already have the responsive documents in hand so it should be a quick turn-around once the negotiations are complete.  You can contact me directly to provide an update prior to re-submitting your request if you like.

FYI:  In your request, you referenced FOIA #GFO-2023-01386-F submitted by Learn Design Apply Inc.  I informed them of this as well and they have agreed to withdrawal and resubmit.  Initially, we thought the negotiations would be complete by November however, the processed has been delayed.

Please let me know how you would like us to proceed.  If however, you would like us to continue processing your request, I will provide GFO's Final Determination, which will inform you officially of our inability to release documents at this time.  Please let me know if you would like to discuss further.
Thanks!
V/r
Dan

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Carver Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Carver Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

communications.subject: RE: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Carver Police Department)
communications.communication:
Good Morning Attorney Stathulis,

The Carver Police Department intentions are to send the information you requested before 2pm today.  I have all the information requested minus one. (the second half of question 6).  I’m waiting to hear back from the school district.  I can send everything I have today minus the one piece of information if you’d like or I can wait until Monday the 29th (the 10 day turnaround timeframe required by law) and hopefully send all of the information.  Please advise which you’d prefer.
Regards,

Michelle

Michelle Sheehan
Records Access Officer
Carver Police Department
3 Center Street
Carver, MA 02330
508-866-2000 ext. 1040

Thank you.

Feel free to contact me if you should require additional information.

Michelle Sheehan

title: Cuba Redress of Injuries

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Cuba Redress of Injuries
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The affidavits of injuries and written statements resulting in payments or denials of the five claims submitted under the 2005 Program for Claims against Cuba. 

Reference of these claims can be found on the DOJ website:

"During the six-month filing period, the Commission received a total of five claims, and denied three of them because they failed to meet the criteria set out in the Secretary of State’s referral letter.  The other two claims did meet those criteria, and after careful review the Commission issued Proposed Decisions certifying the two claims as valid in the total principal amounts of $51,128,926.95 and $16,000.00, respectively.  Neither of the claimants objected to these Proposed Decisions, and they were accordingly entered as final.  After the program’s end in August 2006, the Commission certified these two claims to the Secretary of State, for eventual use in negotiation of a lump-sum claims settlement agreement with the Cuban government. "

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Daniel Boguslaw

communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Boguslaw:



This is in reply to your email dated January 2, 2024, requesting "the affidavits of injuries and written statements resulting in payments or denials of the five claims submitted under the 2005 Program for Claims against Cuba."

You may access the requested files via the following link https://jefs.box.com/s/w0g5a22qn7ri74v2n1yjq25vc8ccpbkn.  Please be advised that we have considered the foreseeable harm standard when reviewing records and applying FOIA exemptions.
If you are not satisfied with Foreign Claims Settlement Commission's determination in response to this request, you may administratively appeal by writing to the Director, Office of Information Policy (OIP), United States Department of Justice, 441 G Street, NW, 6th Floor, Washington, D.C. 20530, or you may submit an appeal through OIP's FOIA STAR portal by creating an account following the instructions on OIP's website: https://www.justice.gov/oip/submit-and-track-request-or-appeal.  Your appeal must be postmarked or electronically transmitted within 90 days of the date of my response to your request.  If you submit your appeal by mail, both the letter and the envelope should be clearly marked "Freedom of Information Act Appeal."
Regards,


Jeremy R. LaFrancois
Chief Administrative Counsel
Foreign Claims Settlement Commission
US Department of Justice
441 G Street, N.W., Room 6330
Washington, D.C. 20579

title: Health and mental healthcare and juvenile justice (New York State Office of Children and Family Services)

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Health and mental healthcare and juvenile justice (New York State Office of Children and Family Services)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern,

This is a request for records under your state public records law.  I am requesting copies of public records regarding health and behavioural health service delivery in youth correctional facilities in your jurisdiction, to inform a comparative research project regarding health and mental health care delivery in juvenile detention facilities across the US. Specifically, I request information regarding the following:
1. Name and contact details for those responsible for health and behavioural health services provisions at all locations where juveniles are incarcerated within your jurisdiction.
2. Regulations, policies and procedures that govern the operation of health and behavioral health provision for juveniles incarcerated within your jurisdiction. This includes health intake, room confinement, medication management,  access to specialist and dental services, discharge planning services, and other health and behavioral health related policies.
3. Contracts from January 1, 2021 to the time the request is filled between your agency and any healthcare provider including both physical health and behavioral health. 
4. Records concerning your jurisdiction’s most recent application to Centre for Medicaid Services (CMS) for an 1115 Medicaid waiver (if applicable), and any response, with specifically focus on how and whether such a waiver applies to provision of Medicaid funded services for detained juveniles.
5. Records relating to financing for health and behavioural health care delivery in your jurisdiction. 

I request the records be provided electronically. If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of the administration of juvenile justice. This information is not being sought for commercial purposes.

If access to the records I am requesting will take longer than allowed by statute, please contact me with information about when I might expect copies of the requested records.

If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law.

Thank you for considering my request.

Sincerely,

Tess Kelly 
Fellow, Harvard FXB Centre for Health and Human Rights 

Joshua Dankoff
Director of Strategic Initiatives
Citizens for Juvenile Justice
617.338.1050

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Longmeadow Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Longmeadow Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

title: FOIA Request: 625 ILCS 5/2-130

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: FOIA Request: 625 ILCS 5/2-130
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

According to 625 ILCS 5/2-130 (https://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/fulltext.asp?DocName=062500050K2-130):

"An ALPR user shall not sell, share, allow access to, or transfer ALPR information to any state or local jurisdiction for the purpose of investigating or enforcing a law that:
        (1) denies or interferes with a person's right to choose or obtain reproductive health care services or any lawful health care services as defined by the Lawful Health Care Activity Act; or
        (2) permits the detention or investigation of a person based on the person's immigration status.
(c) Any ALPR user in this State, including any law enforcement agency of this State that uses ALPR systems, shall not share ALPR information with an out-of-state law enforcement agency without first obtaining a written declaration from the out-of-state law enforcement agency that it expressly affirms that ALPR information obtained shall not be used in a manner that violates subsection (b). If a written declaration of affirmation is not executed, the law enforcement agency shall not share the ALPR information with the out-of-state law enforcement agency."

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

The documents I am seeking include, but are not limited to:

1) Policies and Procedures: Any current policies and procedures that have been adopted to ensure compliance with 625 ILCS 5/2-130.

2) Training Materials: Any training materials provided to staff about 625 ILCS 5/2-130.

3) Written Declarations: Written declarations received from out-of-state law enforcement agencies that it expressly affirms that ALPR information obtained shall not be used in a manner that violates subsection (b) of 625 ILCS 5/2-130.

4) Audit or Compliance Reports: Any recent audit or compliance reports that assess the adherence to 625 ILCS 5/2-130.

5) Records of Violations: Records or reports of any violations of 625 ILCS 5/2-130 legislation, including unauthorized sharing of data.

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (East Longmeadow Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (East Longmeadow Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

communications.subject: Re: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (East Longmeadow Police Department)
communications.communication:
Good Morning,

We have received your request for specific data on school policing

The Department intends to redact some information requested due to the
applicability of the following exemption and the reasons set forth below:

Exemption (a): This exemption applies to records that are "specifically or
by necessary implication exempt from disclosure by statute."

CRIMINAL OFFENDER RECORD INFORMATION In particular, G.L. c. 6, sections
167-178B, and related regulations, requires that criminal justice agencies
withhold any records and data in any communicable form compiled by a
Massachusetts criminal justice agency which concern an identifiable
individual and relate to the nature or disposition of a criminal charge, an
arrest, a pre-trial proceeding, other judicial proceedings, previous
hearings conducted pursuant to section 58A of chapter 276 where the
defendant was detained prior to trial or released with conditions under
subsection (2) of section 58A of chapter 276, sentencing, incarceration,
rehabilitation, or release. Such information shall be restricted to that
recorded in criminal proceedings that are not dismissed before arraignment.
Criminal offender record information shall not include evaluative
information, statistical and analytical reports and files in which
individuals are not directly or indirectly identifiable, or intelligence
information. Criminal offender record information shall be limited to
information concerning persons who have attained the age of 18 and shall
not include any information concerning criminal offenses or acts of
delinquency committed by any person before he attained the age of 18;
provided, however, that if a person under the age of 18 is adjudicated as
an adult, information relating to such criminal offense shall be criminal
offender record information. Criminal offender record information shall not
include information concerning any offenses which are not punishable by
incarceration.

DOMESTIC ABUSE & SEXUAL ASSAULT CASES In particular, G.L. c. 41, section
97D requires law enforcement agencies to keep the following information
confidential. Section 97D provides that "All reports of rape and sexual
assault or attempts to commit such offenses, all reports of abuse
perpetrated by family or household members, as defined in section 1 of
chapter 209A, and all communications between police officers and victims of
such offenses or abuse shall not be public reports and shall be maintained
by the police departments in a manner that shall assure their
confidentiality; provided, however, that all such reports shall be
accessible at all reasonable times, upon written request, to: (i) the
victim, the victim's attorney, others specifically authorized by the victim
to obtain such information, prosecutors and (ii) victim-witness advocates
as defined in section 1 of chapter 258B, domestic violence victims'
counselors as defined in section 20K of chapter 233, sexual assault
counselors as defined in section 20J of chapter 233, if such access is
necessary in the performance of their duties; and provided further, that
all such reports shall be accessible at all reasonable times, upon written,
telephonic, facsimile or electronic mail request to law enforcement
officers, district attorneys or assistant district attorneys and all
persons authorized to admit persons to bail pursuant to section 57 of
chapter 276. Communications between police officers and victims of said
offenses and abuse may also be shared with the forgoing named persons if
such access is necessary in the performance of their duties. A violation of
this section shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than 1 year or
by a fine of not more than $1,000, or both such fine and imprisonment.”



Please see my responses below in blue:

An extract of your records management system or database that includes each
school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during
the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until
the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of
the database to include the following columns:
a. Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b. Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c. Charge (or charges)
d. Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e. Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f. Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g. Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h. Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i. Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law
enforcement
j. Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a
student at the school.
k. Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and
l. Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the
youth to law enforcement, as applicable.



*For Date: 03/21/2022  -  Monday*

*Call Number           Time         Call Reason*

*22-36891                 0818          Initiated - Investigation/Follow Up*

Call Source:    Initiated

Location/Address:    [EAL 0000000001] MAPLE ST

Refer To Arrest:    *22EAL-23-AR*

Arrest:    ANDREWS, LEXY J

Address:    124 NORTH MAIN ST   EAST LONGMEADOW, MA

Age:    18

Charges:    A&B

WITNESS, INTIMIDATE

ROBBERY, UNARMED

3. A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the
police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police
placement or activity in your corresponding school; and,

Attached

4. Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise
describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with
G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

Attached

5. The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer
to each school; and,

Zero cost to the schools

6. The total number of school resource officers and total number of
guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years
2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

1 School Resource Officer

Number of School Guidance Counselors is information under the possession,
custody or control of the School Department.

7. The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in
your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019,
2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and,

2018 – 2019:  2 calls system testing, 14 abandoned 911 calls, 1 medical call

2019 – 2020:  1 call testing alarm. 2 suspicious activity, 16 abandoned 911
calls, 3 medical calls

2020 – 2021:  27 abandoned 911 calls, 3 fire alarm calls, 1 medical call, 1
mv complaint call

2021 – 2022:  2 fire alarm calls, 3 mv crash calls, 42 abandoned 911 calls;
1 disturbance call, 1 medical call, 1 animal complaint call

8. A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional
health support personnel for the school district.

These proposed budget items would be under the possession, custody and
control of the school department

Please be advised that pursuant to 950 CMR 32.00 and G.L. c. 66, section
10A(a) you have the right to appeal this decision to the Supervisor of
Public Records within 90 calendar days. Such appeal shall be in writing,
and shall include a copy of the letter by which the request was made and,
if available, a copy of the letter by which the custodian responded. The
Supervisor shall accept an appeal only from a person who had made his or
her record request in writing. Pursuant to G.L. c. 66, section 10A(c), you
also have the right to seek judicial review by commencing a civil action in
the superior court.

Should you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact me.



Sincerely,



Lori Hall

East Longmeadow Police Department

Records

413 525-5440

communications.subject: Louisiana Public Records Law Request: Brandon Nodier Police Investigative Report
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Louisiana Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Police reports, investigative records and arrest report for Brandon Nodier, date of birth January 1 1954, arrested in April 2012 at the St. Bernard Sheriff's Office in Chalmette and charged with the murder of Dorothy Thompson, 63, on May 2, 1985.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Mikita Brottman
